# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hugh-possingham
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Named in honour of Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen, wife of King William IV, the city was founded in 1836 as the planned capital for a freely settled British colony in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Colonel William Light, one of Adelaide's founding fathers, designed the city centre and chose its location close to the River Torrens.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Light's design, now listed as national heritage, set out the city centre in a grid layout known as "Light's Vision", interspaced by wide boulevards and large public squares, and entirely surrounded by park lands.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Colonial Adelaide was noted for its leading examples of religious freedom and progressive political reforms and became known as the "City of Churches" due to its diversity of faiths.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] It was Australia's third-most populous city until the postwar era.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Today, Adelaide is one of Australia's most visited travel destinations and hosts many festivals and sporting events, such as the Adelaide 500, Tour Down Under, Gather Round, LIV Golf Adelaide, and the Adelaide Fringe, the world's second largest annual arts festival.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide also hosts men's tennis with an ATP 250 event and women's tennis with a WTA 500 event, and will also become the new host of the Australian MotoGP Grand Prix from 2027.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city has also been renowned for its automotive industry, having been the original host of the Australian Grand Prix in the FIA Formula One World Championship from 1985 to 1995.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Other features include its food and wine industries, its coastline and hills, its large defence and manufacturing operations, and its emerging space sector, including the Australian Space Agency being headquartered there.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] With one of the world's largest foreign-born populations, Adelaide has consistently ranked within the top-ten most liveable cities globally for much of the 21st century, being named in 2021 the most liveable city in the country and third in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Its aesthetic appeal has also been recognised by *Architectural Digest*, which ranked Adelaide as the most beautiful city in the world in 2024.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] As South Australia's government and commercial centre, Adelaide is the site of many governmental and financial institutions.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Most of these are concentrated in the central business district along the cultural boulevards of North Terrace and King William Street.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has also been classed as a Gamma + level global city as categorised by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, with the city further linking economic regions to the worldwide economy.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is connected by extensive bus, train and tram networks, all of which are operated by Adelaide Metro, with its main railway terminus at the Adelaide railway station.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city is also served by Adelaide Airport and Port Adelaide, both of which are among the busiest airports and seaports in Australia, respectively.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The amount of time Aboriginal people have been living in the area around modern-day Adelaide has been described as "millennia", "tens of thousands of years", "thousands of generations", or "innumerable generations".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] At Hallett Cove Conservation Park in Adelaide's southern suburbs, archaeological evidence of Aboriginal culture has been found dating back 40,000 years.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The area was originally inhabited by the Kaurna people, one of many Aboriginal tribes in South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city and parklands area also known as *Tarndanyangga* *Tandanya*, *Tarndanya* or *Tarntanya*.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The name means 'male red kangaroo rock', referring to a rock formation on the site that has now been destroyed.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The surrounding area was an open, grassy plain with patches of trees and shrubs, which had been managed by hundreds of generations.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Kaurna country encompassed the plains stretching north and south of Tarntanya, as well as the wooded foothills of the Mt Lofty Ranges.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The River Torrens was known as the Karrawirra Pari (Red Gum forest river).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] About 300 Kaurna populated the Adelaide area, and were referred to by the settlers as the Cowandilla.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The more than 20 local clans across the plain lived seminomadic lives, with extensive mound settlements where huts were built repeatedly over centuries and a complex social structure, including a class of sorcerers separated from regular society.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Within a few decades of European settlement of South Australia, Kaurna culture was almost completely lost, with the last speaker of Kaurna language having died in 1929.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Extensive documentation by early missionaries and other researchers has enabled a modern revival of both, which has included a commitment by local and state governments to rename or include Kaurna names for many local places.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Based on the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield about colonial reform, Robert Gouger petitioned the British government to create a new colony in Australia, resulting in the passage of the South Australia Act 1834.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Physical establishment of the colony began with the arrival of the first British colonisers in February 1836, followed by the commencement of colonial government in South Australia on 28 December 1836.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Proclaimed by the governor near The Old Gum Tree in what is now the suburb of Glenelg North, this day is annually commemorated in South Australia as Proclamation Day.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Named for Queen Adelaide, the site of the colony's capital was surveyed and laid out by Colonel William Light, the first surveyor-general of South Australia, with his own original, unique and topographically sensitive design.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was established as a planned colony of free settlers, promising civil liberties and freedom from religious persecution, based upon the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Wakefield had read accounts of Australian settlement while in prison in London for attempting to abduct an heiress, and realised that the eastern colonies suffered from a lack of available labour, due to the practice of giving land grants to all arrivals.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Wakefield's idea was for the Government to survey and sell the land at a rate that would maintain land values high enough to be unaffordable for labourers and journeymen.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Funds raised from the sale of land were to be used to bring out working-class emigrants, who would have to work hard for the monied settlers to ever afford their own land.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] As a result of this policy, Adelaide does not share the convict settlement history of other Australian cities like Sydney, Brisbane and Hobart.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] As it was believed that in a colony of free settlers there would be little crime, no provision was made for a gaol in Colonel Light's 1837 plan.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] But by mid-1837 the *South Australian Register* was warning of escaped convicts from New South Wales and tenders for a temporary gaol were sought.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Following a burglary, a murder, and two attempted murders in Adelaide during March 1838, Governor Hindmarsh created the South Australian Police Force (now the South Australia Police) in April 1838 under 21-year-old Henry Inman.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The first sheriff, Samuel Smart, was wounded during a robbery, and on 2 May 1838 one of the offenders, Michael Magee, became the first person to be hanged in South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] William Baker Ashton was appointed governor of the temporary gaol in 1839, and in 1840 George Strickland Kingston was commissioned to design Adelaide's new gaol.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Construction of Adelaide Gaol commenced in 1841.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early history was marked by economic uncertainty and questionable leadership.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The first governor of South Australia, John Hindmarsh, clashed frequently with others, in particular the Resident Commissioner, James Hurtle Fisher.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The rural area surrounding Adelaide was surveyed by Light in preparation to sell a total of over 405 km2 (156 sq mi) of land.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early economy started to get on its feet in 1838 with the arrival of livestock from Victoria, New South Wales and Tasmania.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Wool production provided an early basis for the South Australian economy.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] By 1860, wheat farms had been established from Encounter Bay in the south to Clare in the north.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] He was criticised for his response to the Maria massacre.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Gawler was recalled and replaced by George Edward Grey in 1841.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Grey slashed public expenditure against heavy opposition, although its impact was negligible at this point: silver was discovered in Glen Osmond that year, agriculture was well underway, and other mines sprung up all over the state, aiding Adelaide's commercial development.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city exported meat, wool, wine, fruit and wheat by the time Grey left in 1845, contrasting with a low point in 1842 when one-third of Adelaide houses were abandoned.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Trade links with the rest of the Australian states were established after the Murray River was successfully navigated in 1853 by Francis Cadell, an Adelaide resident.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] South Australia became a self-governing colony in 1856 with the ratification of a new constitution by the British parliament.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Secret ballots were introduced, and a bicameral parliament was elected on 9 March 1857, by which time 109,917 people lived in the province.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 1860, the Thorndon Park reservoir was opened, providing an alternative water source to the now turbid River Torrens.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Gas street lighting was implemented in 1867, the University of Adelaide was founded in 1874, the South Australian Art Gallery opened in 1881 and the Happy Valley Reservoir opened in 1896.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In the 1890s Australia was affected by a severe economic depression, ending a hectic era of land booms and tumultuous expansionism.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Financial institutions in Melbourne and banks in Sydney closed.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The national fertility rate fell and immigration was reduced to a trickle.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The value of South Australia's exports nearly halved.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Drought and poor harvests from 1884 compounded the problems, with some families leaving for Western Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was not as badly hit as the larger gold-rush cities of Sydney and Melbourne, and silver and lead discoveries at Broken Hill provided some relief.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Only one year of deficit was recorded, but the price paid was retrenchments and lean public spending.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Wine and copper were the only industries not to suffer a downturn.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was Australia's third largest city for most of the 20th century.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Electric street lighting was introduced in 1900 and electric trams were transporting passengers in 1909.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] 28,000 men were sent to fight in World War I.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Crowley examined the reports of visitors in the early 20th century, noting that "many visitors to Adelaide admired the foresighted planning of its founders", as well as pondering the riches of the young city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide enjoyed a postwar boom, entering a time of relative prosperity.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Its population grew, and it became the third most populous metropolitan area in the country, after Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Its prosperity was short-lived, with the return of droughts and the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] It later returned to fortune under strong government leadership.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Secondary industries helped reduce the state's dependence on primary industries.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] World War II brought industrial stimulus and diversification to Adelaide under the Playford Government, which advocated Adelaide as a safe place for manufacturing due to its less vulnerable location.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Shipbuilding was expanded at the nearby port of Whyalla.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The South Australian Government in this period built on former wartime manufacturing industries but neglected cultural facilities which meant South Australia's economy lagged behind.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] International manufacturers like Holden and Chrysler made use of these factories around the Adelaide area in suburbs like Elizabeth, completing its transformation from an agricultural service centre to a 20th-century motor city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Mannum–Adelaide pipeline brought River Murray water to Adelaide in 1955 and an airport opened at West Beach in 1955.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Flinders University and the Flinders Medical Centre were established in the 1960s at Bedford Park, south of the city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Today, Flinders Medical Centre is one of the largest teaching hospitals in South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In the post-war years around the early 1960s, Adelaide was surpassed by Brisbane as Australia's third largest city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Dunstan Governments of the 1970s saw something of an Adelaide "cultural revival", establishing a wide array of social reforms.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city became noted for its progressivism as South Australia became the first Australian state or territory to decriminalise homosexuality between consenting adults in 1975.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide became a centre for the arts, building upon the biennial "Adelaide Festival of Arts" that commenced in 1960.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The State Bank collapsed in 1991 during an economic recession.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The effects lasted until 2004, when Standard & Poor's reinstated South Australia's AAA credit rating.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's tallest building, completed in 2020, is called the Adelaidean and is located at 11 Frome Street.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In the early years of the 21st century, a significant increase in the state government's spending on Adelaide's infrastructure occurred.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Rann government invested A$535 million in a major upgrade of the Adelaide Oval to enable Australian Football League to be played in the city centre and more than A$2 billion to build a new Royal Adelaide Hospital on land adjacent to the Adelaide Railway Station.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Glenelg tramline was extended through the city to Hindmarsh down to East Terrace and the suburban railway line extended south to Seaford.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Following a period of stagnation in the 1990s and 2000s, Adelaide began several major developments and redevelopments.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Convention Centre was redeveloped and expanded at a cost of A$350 million beginning in 2012.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The government invested more than A$2 billion to build a desalination plant, powered by renewable energy, as an "insurance policy" against droughts affecting Adelaide's water supply.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Festival, Fringe, and Womadelaide became annual events.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is north of the Fleurieu Peninsula, on the Adelaide Plains between the Gulf St Vincent and the relatively low-lying Mount Lofty Ranges (Mount Lofty, the highest point, is 710 metres above sea level).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city stretches 20 km (12 mi) from the coast to the foothills, and 90 km (56 mi) from Gawler at its northern extent to Sellicks Beach in the south.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city sits at an average elevation of 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Mount Lofty, east of the Adelaide metropolitan region in the Adelaide Hills at an elevation of 727 metres (2,385 ft), is the tallest point of the city and in the state south of Burra.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city borders the Temperate Grassland of South Australia in the east, an endangered vegetation community.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Much of Adelaide was bushland before British settlement, with some variation – sandhills, swamps and marshlands were prevalent around the coast.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The loss of the sandhills to urban development had a particularly destructive effect on the coastline due to erosion.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Where practical, the government has implemented programs to rebuild and vegetate sandhills at several of Adelaide's beachside suburbs.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Tennyson Dunes is the largest contiguous, tertiary dune system contained entirely within Metropolitan Adelaide, providing refuge for a variety of remnant species formerly found along the entire coastline.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Much of the original vegetation has been cleared with what is left to be found in reserves such as the Cleland National Park and Belair National Park.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] A number of creeks and rivers flow through the Adelaide region.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The largest are the Torrens and Onkaparinga catchments.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide relies on its many reservoirs for water supply with the Happy Valley Reservoir supplying around 40% and the much larger Mount Bold Reservoir 10% of Adelaide's domestic requirements respectively.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide and its surrounding area is one of the most seismically active regions in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] On 1 March 1954 at 3:40 am Adelaide experienced its largest recorded earthquake to date, with the epicentre 12 km from the city centre at Darlington, and a reported magnitude of 5.6.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Most of the Adelaide metropolitan area lies in the downthrown St Vincent Basin and its embayments, including the Adelaide Plains Sub-basin, and the Golden Grove, Noarlunga and Willunga Embayments.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] These basins contain deposits of Tertiary marine and non-marine sands and limestones, which form important aquifers.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a planned city, designed by the first Surveyor-General of South Australia, Colonel William Light.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] His plan, sometimes referred to as "Light's Vision" (also the name of a statue of him on Montefiore Hill), arranged Adelaide in a grid, with five squares in the Adelaide city centre and a ring of parks, known as the Adelaide Parklands, surrounding it.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Light's selection of the location for the city was initially unpopular with the early settlers, as well as South Australia's first governor, John Hindmarsh, due to its distance from the harbour at Port Adelaide, and the lack of fresh water there.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Light successfully persisted with his choice of location against this initial opposition.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The benefits of Light's design are numerous: Adelaide has had wide multi-lane roads from its beginning, an easily navigable cardinal direction grid layout and an expansive green ring around the city centre.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] There are two sets of ring roads in Adelaide that have resulted from the original design.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The inner ring route (A21) borders the parklands, and the outer route (A3/A13/A16/A17) completely bypasses the inner city via (in clockwise order) Grand Junction Road, Hampstead Road, Ascot Avenue, Portrush Road, Cross Road and South Road.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Suburban expansion has to some extent outgrown Light's original plan.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Numerous former outlying villages and "country towns", as well as the satellite city of Elizabeth, have been enveloped by its suburban sprawl.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Expanding developments in the Adelaide Hills region led to the construction of the South Eastern Freeway to cope with growth, which has subsequently led to new developments and further improvements to that transport corridor.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Similarly, the booming development in Adelaide's South led to the construction of the Southern Expressway.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] New roads are not the only transport infrastructure developed to cope with the urban growth.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The O-Bahn Busway and Adelaide Metro are examples of a unique solution to Tea Tree Gully's transport woes in the 1980s.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The development of the nearby suburb of Golden Grove in the late 1980s followed a planned approach to urban growth.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In the 1960s, a Metropolitan Adelaide Transport Study Plan was proposed to cater for the future growth of the city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The plan involved the construction of freeways, expressways and the upgrade of certain aspects of the public transport system.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The then premier Steele Hall approved many parts of the plan and the government went as far as purchasing land for the project.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The later Labor government elected under Don Dunstan shelved the plan, but allowed the purchased land to remain vacant, should the future need for freeways arise.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 1980, the Liberal party won government and premier David Tonkin committed his government to selling off the land acquired for the MATS plan, ensuring that even when needs changed, the construction of most MATS-proposed freeways would be impractical.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Some parts of this land have been used for transport, (e.g. the O-Bahn Busway and Southern Expressway), while most has been progressively subdivided for residential use.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 2008, the SA Government announced plans for a network of transport-oriented developments across the Adelaide metropolitan area and purchased a 10 hectare industrial site at Bowden for $52.5 million as the first of these developments.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Historically, Adelaide's suburban residential areas have been characterised by single-storey detached houses built on 1,000-square-metre (1⁄4-acre) blocks.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] A relative lack of suitable, locally available timber for construction purposes led to the early development of a brick-making industry, as well as the use of stone, for houses and other buildings.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] By 1891, 68% of houses were built of stone, 15% of timber, and 10% of brick, with brick also being widely used in stone houses for quoins, door and window surrounds, and chimneys and fireplaces.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] There is a wide variety in the styles of these houses.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Until the 1960s, most of the more substantial houses were built of red brick, though many front walls were of ornamental stone.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Then cream bricks became fashionable, and in the 1970s, deep red and brown bricks became popular.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Until the 1970s, roofs tended to be clad with (painted) corrugated iron or cement or clay tiles, usually red "terracotta".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Since then, Colorbond corrugated steel has dominated.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Up to the 1970s, most houses were of "double brick" construction on concrete footings, with timber floors laid on joists supported by "dwarf walls".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The use of precast concrete panels for floor and wall construction has also increased.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In addition to this, a significant factor in Adelaide's suburban history is the role of the South Australian Housing Trust.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city has hot, dry summers and cool winters with moderate rainfall.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Most rain falls in the winter months, leading to the suggestion that the climate be classified as a "cold monsoon".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Rainfall is unreliable, light and infrequent throughout summer, although heavy falls can occur.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The winter has fairly reliable rainfall with June being the wettest month of the year, averaging around 80 mm.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Frosts are occasional, with the most notable occurrences in 1908 and 1982.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a windy city with significant wind chill in winter, which makes the temperature seem colder than it actually is.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Snowfall in the metropolitan area is extremely rare, although light and sporadic falls in the nearby hills and at Mount Lofty occur during winter.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Dewpoints in the summer typically range from 8 to 10 °C (46 to 50 °F).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] There are usually several days in summer where the temperature reaches 40.0 °C (104.0 °F) or above.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] While conditions vary from year-to-year, a warming trend has been increasing in recent years, and with drought conditions experienced in SA in 2024−25, Adelaide has had to rely on desalination to augment its water supply.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The city features 90.6 clear days annually.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The average sea temperature ranges from 13.7 °C (56.7 °F) in August to 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) in February.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was consistently ranked in the world's 10 most liveable cities through the 2010s by The Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In June 2021, *The Economist* ranked Adelaide the third most liveable city in the world, behind Auckland and Osaka.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In June 2023, Adelaide was ranked the twelfth most liveable city in the world by the Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In December 2021, Adelaide was named the world's second National Park City, after the state government had lobbied for this title.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] It was ranked the most liveable city in Australia by the Property Council of Australia, based on surveys of residents' views of their own city, between 2010 and 2013, dropping to second place in 2014.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide, as the capital of South Australia, is the seat of the Government of South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The bicameral Parliament of South Australia consists of the lower house known as the House of Assembly and the upper house known as the Legislative Council.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] General elections are held every four years, the last being the 2022 South Australian state election.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] As Adelaide is South Australia's capital and most populous city, the State Government co-operates extensively with the City of Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 2006, the Ministry for the City of Adelaide was created to facilitate the State Government's collaboration with the Adelaide City Council and the Lord Mayor to improve Adelaide's image.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The State Parliament's Capital City Committee is also involved in the governance of the City of Adelaide, being primarily concerned with the planning of Adelaide's urban development and growth.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Reflecting South Australia's status as Australia's most centralised state, Adelaide elects a substantial majority of the South Australian House of Assembly.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Of the 47 seats in the chamber, 34 seats (three-quarters of the legislature) are based in Adelaide, and two rural seats include Adelaide suburbs.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide metropolitan area is divided between nineteen local government areas.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] At its centre, the City of Adelaide administers the Adelaide city centre, North Adelaide, and the surrounding Adelaide Parklands.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] It is the oldest municipal authority in Australia and was established in 1840, when Adelaide and Australia's first mayor, James Hurtle Fisher, was elected.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] From 1919 onwards, the city has had a Lord Mayor, the current being Lord Mayor *The Right Honourable* Jane Lomax-Smith.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants are known as Adelaideans.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Compared with Australia's other state capitals, Adelaide is growing at a rate similar to Sydney and Hobart (see List of cities in Australia by population).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 2024, it had a metropolitan population (including suburbs) of 1,469,163, making it Australia's fifth-largest city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] 77% of the population of South Australia are residents of the Adelaide metropolitan area, making South Australia one of the most centralised states.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Major areas of population growth in recent years have been in outer suburbs such as Mawson Lakes and Golden Grove.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants occupy 366,912 houses, 57,695 semi-detached, row terrace or town houses and 49,413 flats, units or apartments.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] About one sixth (17.1%) of the population had university qualifications.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The number of Adelaideans with vocational qualifications (such as tradespersons) fell from 62.1% of the labour force in the 1991 census to 52.4% in the 2001 census.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is aging more rapidly than other Australian capital cities.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] More than a quarter (27.5%) of Adelaide's population is aged 55 years or older, in comparison to the national average of 25.6%.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has the lowest number of children (under-15-year-olds), who comprised 17.7% of the population, compared to the national average of 19.3%.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Overseas-born Adelaideans composed 31.3% of the total population at the 2021 census.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The five largest groups of overseas-born were from England (5.7%), India (3.1%), Mainland China (1.8%), Vietnam (1.2%) and Italy (1.1%).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Suburbs including Newton, Payneham and Campbelltown in the east and Torrensville, West Lakes and Fulham to the west, have large Greek and Italian communities.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Italian consulate is located in the western suburb of Hindmarsh.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Large Vietnamese populations are settled in the north-western suburbs of Woodville, Kilkenny, Pennington, Mansfield Park and Athol Park and also Parafield Gardens and Pooraka in Adelaide's north.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Migrants from India and Sri Lanka have settled into inner suburban areas of Adelaide including the inner northern suburbs of Blair Athol, Kilburn and Enfield and the inner southern suburbs of Plympton, Park Holme and Kurralta Park.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Suburbs such as Para Hills, Salisbury, Ingle Farm and Blair Athol in the north and Findon, West Croydon and Seaton and other Western suburbs have sizeable Afghan communities.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Chinese migrants favour settling in the eastern and north eastern suburbs including Kensington Gardens, Greenacres, Modbury and Golden Grove.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Mawson Lakes has a large international student population, due to its proximity to the University of South Australia campus.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] At the 2021 census, 1.7% of Adelaide's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] At the 2016 census, 75.4% of the population spoke English at home.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The other languages most commonly spoken at home were Italian (2.1%), Standard Mandarin (2.1%), Greek (1.7%) Vietnamese (1.4%), and Cantonese (0.7%).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Kaurna language, spoken by the area's original inhabitants, had no living speakers in the middle of the 20th century, but since the 1990s there has been a sustained revival effort from academics and Kaurna elders.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was founded on a vision of religious tolerance that attracted a wide variety of religious practitioners.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] This led to it being known as *The City of Churches*.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] But approximately 28% of the population expressed no religious affiliation in the 2011 Census, compared with the national average of 22.3%, making Adelaide one of Australia's least religious cities.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] According to 2021 census, 39.8% of the population of Adelaide identify as Christian, with the largest denominations being Catholic (16.4%), Anglican (7.0%), Uniting Church (3.9%) and Greek Orthodox (2.4%).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Non-Christian faith communities, representing 9.5% from Adelaide's population, include Islam (2.8%), Hinduism (2.7%) and Buddhism (2.3%).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Jewish community of the city dates back to 1840.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Eight years later, 58 Jews lived in the city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] A synagogue was built in 1871, when 435 Jews lived in the city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Many took part in the city councils, such as Judah Moss Solomon (1852–66).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Three Jews have been elected to the position of city mayor.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 1968, the Jewish population of Adelaide numbered about 1,200; in 2001, according to the Australian census, 979 persons declared themselves to be Jewish by religion.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 2011, over 1,000 Jews were living in the city, served by an Orthodox synagogue, Adelaide Hebrew Congregation and a Reform synagogue, **Beit Shalom**, in addition to a virtual Jewish museum.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Massada College, a Jewish day school opened in the city in 1976 and closed in 2011.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Holocaust Museum and Andrew Steiner Education Centre opened in 2020.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The "Afghan" community in Australia first became established in the 1860s when camels and their Pathan, Punjabi, Baluchi and Sindhi handlers began to be used to open up settlement in the continent's arid interior.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Until eventually superseded by the advent of the railways and motor vehicles, camels played an invaluable economic and social role in transporting heavy loads of goods to and from isolated settlements and mines.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] This is acknowledged by the name of The Ghan, the passenger train operating between Adelaide, Alice Springs, and Darwin.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Central Adelaide Mosque is regarded as Australia's oldest permanent mosque; an earlier mosque at Marree in northern South Australia, dating from 1861 to 1862 and subsequently abandoned or demolished, has now been rebuilt.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] South Australia's largest employment sectors are health care and social assistance, surpassing manufacturing in SA as the largest employer since 2006–07.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 2009–10, manufacturing in SA had average annual employment of 83,700 persons compared with 103,300 for health care and social assistance.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Health care and social assistance represented nearly 13% of the state average annual employment.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Hills wine region is an iconic and viable economic region for both the state and country in terms of wine production and sale.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The retail trade is the second largest employer in SA (2009–10), with over 91,900 jobs, and 12 per cent of the state workforce.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Manufacturing, defence technology, high-tech electronic systems and research, commodity export and corresponding service industries all play a role in the SA economy.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Almost half of all cars produced in Australia were made in Adelaide at the Holden Elizabeth Plant in Elizabeth.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The site ceased operating in November 2017.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The collapse of the State Bank in 1992 resulted in large levels of state public debt (as much as A$4 billion).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The collapse meant that successive governments enacted lean budgets, cutting spending, which was a setback to the further economic development of the city and state.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] As of January 2026, the government has an AA+ credit rating.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The global media conglomerate News Corporation was founded in, and until 2004 incorporated in, Adelaide, and the city is still considered the Corporation's "spiritual" home by its founder, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Australia's largest oil company, Santos, prominent South Australian brewery, Coopers, and national retailer Harris Scarfe also call Adelaide their home.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] In 2018, at which time more than 80 organisations employed 800 people in the space sector in South Australia, Adelaide was chosen for the headquarters of a new Australian Space Agency.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] It is working to triple the size of the Australian space industry and create 20,000 new jobs by 2030.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is home to a large proportion of Australia's defence industries, which contribute over A$1 billion to South Australia's Gross State Product.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Others, such as Saab Systems and Raytheon, are in or near Technology Park.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] ASC Pty Ltd, is based in the industrial suburb of Osborne and is also a part of Technology Park.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] South Australia was charged with constructing Australia's *Collins*-class submarines and more recently the A$6 billion contract to construct the Royal Australian Navy's new air-warfare destroyers.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] As of November 2015, Greater Adelaide had an unemployment rate of 7.4% with a youth unemployment rate of 15%.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The median weekly individual income for people aged 15 years and over was $447 per week in 2006, compared with $466 nationally.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The median family income was $1,137 per week, compared with $1,171 nationally.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's housing and living costs are substantially lower than that of other Australian cities, with housing being notably cheaper.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The median Adelaide house price is half that of Sydney and two-thirds that of Melbourne.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The three-month trend unemployment rate to March 2007 was 6.2%.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] The Northern suburbs' unemployment rate is disproportionately higher than the other regions of Adelaide at 8.3%, while the East and South are lower than the Adelaide average at 4.9% and 5.0% respectively.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Over the decade March 2001 – March 2010, Metropolitan Adelaide median house prices approximately tripled.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] 11%p.a. compounding) In the five years March 2007 – March 2012, prices increased by approx.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] March 2012 – March 2017 saw a further increase of 19% – approx.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] no longer release a median house price for the Adelaide Metropolitan area, so figures retrieved are from Dept of the Premier and Cabinet.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Each quarter, The Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA) publishes a list of median house sale prices by suburb and Local Government Area.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p01] Quarterly Reports for the last two years can be found on the REISA website.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Education forms an increasingly important part of the city's economy, with the South Australian Government and educational institutions attempting to position Adelaide as "Australia's education hub" and marketing it as a "Learning City".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The number of international students studying in Adelaide has increased rapidly in recent years to 30,726 in 2015, of which 1,824 were secondary school students.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the birthplace of three Nobel laureates, more than any other Australian city: physicist William Lawrence Bragg and pathologists Howard Florey and Robin Warren, all of whom completed secondary and tertiary education at St Peter's College and the University of Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also the hometown of mathematician Terence Tao.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] There are two systems of primary and secondary schools, a public system operated by the South Australian Government's Department for Education, and a private system of independent and Catholic schools.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] South Australian schools provide education under the Australian Curriculum for reception to Year 10 students.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In Years 10 to 12, students study for the South Australian Certificate of Education (SACE).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] They have the option of incorporating vocational education and training (VET) courses or a flexible learning option (FLO).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has 24 schools that use International Baccalaureate programs as an alternative to the Australian Curriculum or SACE.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] These programs include the IB Primary Years Programme, the IB Middle Years Programme, and the IB Diploma Programme.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] For South Australian students who cannot attend a traditional school, including students who live in rural or remote areas, the state government runs the Open Access College (OAC), which provides virtual teaching.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The OAC has a campus in Marden which caters to students from reception to Year 12 and adults who haven't been able to complete their SACE.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Guardians are also able to apply for their child to be educated from home as long as they provide an education program which meets the same requirements as the Australian Curriculum as well as opportunities for social interaction.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] There are two public universities local to Adelaide, as well as one private university and three constituent colleges of foreign universities.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Flinders University of South Australia, Adelaide University and Torrens University Australia—part of the Laureate International Universities are based in Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The University of Adelaide was ranked in the top 150 universities worldwide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Flinders ranked in the top 250 and Uni SA in the top 300.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Torrens University Australia is part of an international network of over 70 higher education institutions in more than 30 countries worldwide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide University is a recent amalgamation between the University of Adelaide and the University of South Australia, ranked in the top 150 globally and top 10 nationally.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Today, it stands as Australia's third-oldest university and a member of the leading "Group of Eight".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The merged university has over 64,000 students and two main campuses on North Terrace, with many other campuses across South Australia, including in Whyalla and Mount Gambier.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The two universities had multiple proposals to merge into a single university.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] A proposal in 2018 failed due to uncertainty as to the new name and leadership of the merged university.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2022, the universities announced a new merger proposal, with the name and leadership issues settled and support from the South Australian government.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Flinders University, with 25,184 students, is based in the southern suburb of Bedford Park, alongside the Flinders Medical Centre, with additional campuses in neighbouring Tonsley and in Victoria Square in the city centre.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2024, the University of the Sunshine Coast opened a new campus in Adelaide where undergraduate and master's courses in ICT and business are offered.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of Divinity is at Brooklyn Park.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] There are several South Australian TAFE (Technical and Further Education) campuses in the metropolitan area that provide a range of vocational education and training.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of the Arts, as a school of TAFE SA, provides nationally recognised training in visual and performing arts.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Workers' Educational Association of South Australia (WEA-SA) is an independent not-for-profit adult education organisation based in Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Established in 1913, it is one of Australia's longest running providers of community-based adult learning.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] WEA-SA delivers short courses, lectures, cultural programs, travel and interest clubs designed to promote lifelong learning.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] StudyAdelaide, a collaboration between the South Australian government and the tertiary education sector, maintains an on-line list of schools, universities, and higher education institutions in SA.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In addition to the universities, Adelaide is home to research institutes, including the Royal Institution of Australia, established in 2009 as a counterpart to the two-hundred-year-old Royal Institution of Great Britain.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] While established as a British province, and very much English in terms of its culture, Adelaide attracted immigrants from other parts of Europe early on, including German and other European non-conformists escaping religious persecution.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The first German Lutherans arrived in 1838, bringing with them the vine cuttings that they used to found the acclaimed wineries of the Barossa Valley.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Royal Adelaide Show is an annual agricultural show and state fair, established in 1839 and now a huge event held in the Adelaide Showground annually.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's arts scene flourished in the 1960s and 1970s with the support of successive premiers from both major political parties.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The renowned Adelaide Festival of Arts was established in 1960 under Thomas Playford, which in the same year spawned an unofficial uncurated series of performances and exhibits which grew into the Adelaide Fringe.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Construction of the Adelaide Festival Centre began under Steele Hall in 1970 and was completed under the subsequent government of Don Dunstan, who also established the South Australian Film Corporation in 1972 and the State Opera of South Australia in 1976.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] With the Festival, the Fringe, WOMADelaide, Writers' Week and the Adelaide 500 street motor racing event (along with evening music concerts) all happening in early March, the period became known colloquially as "Mad March".
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2014, Ghil'ad Zuckermann founded the Adelaide Language Festival.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] There are many international cultural fairs, most notably the German Schützenfest and Greek Glendi.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide holds an annual Christmas pageant, the world's largest Christmas parade.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] As the state capital, Adelaide has a great number of cultural institutions, many of them along the boulevard of North Terrace.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Art Gallery of South Australia, with about 35,000 works, holds Australia's second largest state-based collection.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adjacent are the South Australian Museum and State Library of South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Botanic Garden, National Wine Centre and Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute are nearby in the East End of the city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In the back of the State Library lies the Migration Museum, Australia's oldest museum of its kind.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Further west, the Lion Arts Centre is home to ACE Open, which showcases contemporary art; Dance Hub SA; and other studios and arts industry spaces.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Mercury Cinema and the JamFactory ceramics and design gallery are just around the corner.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Festival Centre (which includes the Dunstan Playhouse, Festival Theatre and Space Theatre), on the banks of the Torrens, is the focal point for much of the cultural activity in the city and home to the State Theatre Company of South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Other live music and theatre venues include the Adelaide Entertainment Centre; Adelaide Oval; Memorial Drive Park; Thebarton Theatre; Adelaide Town Hall; Her Majesty's Theatre; Queen's Theatre; Holden Street Theatres; and the Hopgood Theatre.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Lion Arts Factory, within the Lion Arts Centre, hosts contemporary music in a wide range of genres, as does "The Gov" in Hindmarsh.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The city also has numerous smaller theatres, pubs and cabaret bars which host performances.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2015, it was said that there were now more live music venues per capita in Adelaide than any other capital city in the southern hemisphere, *Lonely Planet* labelled Adelaide "Australia's live music city", and the city was recognised as a "City of Music" by the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Although there were many pubs hosting live music in the CBD in past, the number has slowly diminished.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Grace Emily on Waymouth Street, which was refurbished as a live music venue around 2000, is popular with musicians and patrons alike.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Crown & Anchor ("the Cranker") was saved from demolition in 2024 after a vigorous campaign by the public as well as many musicians and politicians.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] New legislation passed on 11 September 2024 designates the entire Adelaide CBD as a "live music venue area", and gives protection to selected live music venues.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In addition to its own WOMAD (WOMADelaide), Adelaide has attracted several touring music festivals, including Creamfields, Laneway, and Groovin' (some since defunct).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has produced musical groups and individuals who have achieved national and international fame.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Noted rocker Jimmy Barnes (formerly lead vocalist with Cold Chisel) spent most of his youth in the northern suburb of Elizabeth.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Australian singer-songwriter Paul Kelly grew up in Adelaide and was head prefect at Rostrevor College.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The first *Australian Idol* winner, Guy Sebastian, hails from the north-eastern suburb of Golden Grove.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] All of the five Australian national television networks broadcast both high-definition digital and standard-definition digital television services in Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] They share three transmission towers on the ridge near the summit of Mount Lofty.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] There are two other transmission sites at 25 Grenfell Street, Adelaide and Elizabeth Downs.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The two government-funded stations are run by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC South Australia) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Seven Network and Network Ten both own their Adelaide stations (SAS-7 and ADS-10 respectively).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's NWS-9 is part of the Nine Network.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has a community television station, Channel 44.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] As part of a nationwide phase-out of analogue television in Australia, Adelaide's analogue television service was shut down on 2 April 2013.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] There are 20 radio stations that serve the metropolitan area, as well as four stations that serve only parts of the metropolitan area; six commercial stations, six community stations, six national stations and two narrowcast stations.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] DAB+ digital radio has been broadcasting in metropolitan Adelaide since 20 May 2009, and currently offers a choice of 41 stations all operated by the existing licensed radio broadcasters, which includes high-quality simulcast of all AM and FM stations.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The main sports played professionally in Adelaide are Australian Rules football, soccer, cricket, netball, and basketball.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the home of two Australian Football League teams: the Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club, and one A-League soccer team, Adelaide United.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] A local Australian rules football league, the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), is made up of 10 teams from around Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The SANFL has been in operation since 1877 when it began as the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) before changing its name to the SANFL in 1927.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code played in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Since completion of the upgrade, home games for Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide now take place at Adelaide Oval.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Since 1884, Adelaide Oval has also hosted an international cricket test every summer, along with a number of One Day International cricket matches.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Memorial Drive Park, adjacent to the Adelaide Oval, used to host Davis Cup and other major tennis events, including the Australian Open and the Adelaide International.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's professional association football team, Adelaide United, play in the A-League.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Founded in 2003, their home ground is Coopers Stadium, which has a capacity of 16,500 and is one of the few purpose-built soccer stadia in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Prior to United's foundation, Adelaide City and West Adelaide represented the city in the National Soccer League.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The two sides, which contest the Adelaide derby against one another, now play in the National Premier Leagues South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] For two years, 1997 and 1998, Adelaide was represented in Australia's top level rugby league, after the New South Wales Rugby League had played a single game per season at the Adelaide Oval for five years starting in 1991.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Rams were formed and played in the breakaway Super League (SL) competition in 1997 before moving to the new National Rugby League in 1998.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Initially playing at the Adelaide Oval, the club moved to the more suitable Hindmarsh Stadium late in the 1998 season.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] As part of a peace deal with the Australian Rugby League to end the Super League war, the club's owners News Limited (who were also owners of the SL) suddenly closed the club only weeks before the start of the 1999 season.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has two professional basketball teams, the men's team being the Adelaide 36ers which plays in the National Basketball League (NBL) and the women's team, the Adelaide Lightning which plays in the Women's National Basketball League (WNBL).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide 36ers play at the Adelaide Entertainment Centre while the Adelaide Lightning play at the Adelaide Arena (Previously Titanium Security Arena).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has a professional netball team, the Adelaide Thunderbirds, which plays in the national netball competition, the Super Netball championship, with home games played at Netball SA Stadium.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Thunderbirds occasionally play games or finals at the Titanium Security Arena, while international netball matches are usually played at the 10,500 seat Adelaide Entertainment Centre.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Titanium Security Arena has a capacity of 8,000 and is the largest purpose-built basketball stadium in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Since 1999 Adelaide and its surrounding areas have hosted the Tour Down Under bicycle race, organised and directed by Adelaide-based Michael Turtur.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Turtur won an Olympic gold medal for Australia in the 4000 m team pursuit at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Tour Down Under is the largest cycling event outside Europe and was the first event outside Europe to be granted UCI ProTour status.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The 2024 Women's Tour Down Under cycle stage race was held in and around Adelaide, South Australia from 12 to 14 January 2024.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide maintains a franchise in the Australian Baseball League, the Adelaide Giants.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] They have been playing since 2009, and their home stadium (until 2016) was Norwood Oval.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] From 2016 the team moved to the Diamond Sports Stadium located near the Adelaide International Airport due to renovations at Norwood.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has an ice hockey team, Adelaide Adrenaline in the Australian Ice Hockey League (AIHL).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It was national champions in 2009 and plays its games at the IceArenA.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Australian Grand Prix for World Championship Formula One racing was hosted by Adelaide from 1985 to 1995 on the Adelaide Street Circuit which was laid out in the city's East End as well as the eastern parklands including the Victoria Park Racecourse.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Grand Prix became a source of pride, and losing the event to Melbourne in a surprise announcement in mid-1993 left a void that has since been filled with the Adelaide 500 for V8 Supercar racing, held on a modified version of the same street circuit.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Classic Adelaide, a rally of classic sporting vehicles, is also held in the city and its surrounds.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide formerly had three horse racing venues.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Victoria Park, Cheltenham Park Racecourse, both of which have now closed, and Morphettville Racecourse that remains the home of the South Australian Jockey Club.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It also has Globe Derby Park for Harness racing that opened in 1969, and by 1973 had become Adelaide's premier harness racing venue taking over from the Wayville Showgrounds, as well as Greyhound Park for greyhound racing that opened in 1972.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The World Solar Challenge race attracts teams from around the world, most of which are fielded by universities or corporations, although some are fielded by high schools.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The race has a 20-years' history spanning nine races, with the inaugural event taking place in 1987.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide hosted the 2012 World Bowls Championships at Lockleys Bowling Club, becoming the third city in the world to have held the championships twice, having previously hosted the event in 1996.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Dirt track speedway is also popular in Adelaide with three operating speedways.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Motorsport Park, located adjacent to the Adelaide International Raceway road racing circuit at Virginia (24 km (15 mi) north of the city centre) has been in continuous operation since 1979 after the closure of the popular Rowley Park Speedway.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Gillman Speedway located in the semi-industrial suburb of Gillman, has been in operation since 1998 and caters to Motorcycle speedway and Sidecars, while the Sidewinders Speedway located in Wingfield is also a motorcycle speedway dedicated to Under-16 riders and has been in operation since 1978.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2016, backed by South Australia's Peregrine Corporation opened up a multi-purpose facility; a state-of-the-art motorsporting park and a hotel alongside its newer OTR service station outside a small township of Tailem Bend currently named The Bend Motorsport Park.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Design for thrill seekers and rev-heads the facility currently host South Australia's second Supercars motoring event during a round in August.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is home to the Great Southern Slam, the world's largest roller derby tournament.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The tournament has been held biennially over Australia's Queen's Birthday holiday weekend since 2010.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2014, and 2016 the tournament featured 45 teams playing in two divisions.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2018, the tournament has expanded to 48 teams competing in three divisions.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Being centrally located on the Australian mainland, Adelaide forms a strategic transport hub for east–west and north–south routes.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The city itself has a metropolitan public transport system managed by and known as the Adelaide Metro.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Tramways were largely dismantled in the 1950s, but saw a revival in the 2010s with upgrades and extensions.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Road transport in Adelaide has historically been easier than many of the other Australian cities, with a well-defined city layout and wide multiple-lane roads from the beginning of its development.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide was known as a "twenty-minute city", with commuters having been able to travel from metropolitan outskirts to the city proper in roughly twenty minutes.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] However, such arterial roads often experience traffic congestion as the city grows.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has one freeway and four expressways.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has two commercial airports, Adelaide Airport and Parafield Airport.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Airport, in Adelaide's south-western suburbs, serves almost 9 million passengers annually, with an extensive number of direct flight routes within Australia, as well as other destinations in Oceania, Asia and North America.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport, Adelaide's second airport 18 kilometres (11 miles) north of the city centre, is used for small aircraft, pilot training and recreational aviation purposes.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport served as Adelaide's main aerodrome until the opening of the Adelaide Airport in February 1955.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also home to a military airport, known as RAAF Base Edinburgh, located in the northern suburbs.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It was built in 1955 in a joint initiative with the United Kingdom for weapon development.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's two largest hospitals are the Royal Adelaide Hospital (RAH) in Adelaide Parklands, a teaching hospital affiliated with the University of Adelaide (800 beds), and the Flinders Medical Centre (580 beds) at Bedford Park, affiliated with Flinders University.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The RAH also operates additional campuses for specialist care throughout the suburbs including the Hampstead Rehabilitation Centre (150 beds) at Northfield and the Glenside Campus (129 beds) for acute mental health services.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Other major public hospitals are the Women's and Children's Hospital (305 beds), at North Adelaide; the Queen Elizabeth Hospital (340 beds) at Woodville; Modbury Hospital (174 beds) at Modbury; and the Lyell McEwin Hospital (198 beds) at Elizabeth Vale.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Numerous private hospitals are also located throughout the city, with the largest operators being not-for-profits Adelaide Community Healthcare Alliance (three hospitals) and Calvary Care (four hospitals).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2017, the RAH was relocated from the city's East End to a new AU$2.3 billion facility built over former railyards in the West End.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] SAHMRI, with additional external funding, has built a $300 million second facility completed in 2024, which was intended to house the Australian Bragg Centre with Australia's first proton therapy unit.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Construction is underway for the Women's and Children's Hospital to be relocated to the precinct adjacent the RAH by 2030.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The largest provider of community health care within Adelaide is the not-for-profit Royal District Nursing Service, which provides out of hospital care and hospital avoidance care.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's energy requirements were originally met by the Adelaide Electric Supply Company, which was nationalised by the Playford government in 1946, becoming the Electricity Trust of South Australia (ETSA).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The electricity retail market was opened to competition in 2003 and although competition was expected to result in lower retail costs, prices increased by 23.7% in the market's first year.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2004, the privatisation was deemed to be a failure with consumers paying 60% more for their power and with the state government estimated to lose $3 billion in power generation net income in the first ten years of privatisation.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2012, the industry came under scrutiny for allegedly reducing supply by shutting down generators during periods of peak demand to force prices up.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Increased media attention also revealed that in 2009 the state government had approved a 46% increase in retail prices to cover expected increases in the costs of generation while generation costs had in fact fallen 35% by 2012.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] South Australia has the highest retail price for electricity in the country.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Privatisation led to competition from a variety of companies who now separately provide for the generation, transmission, distribution and retail sales of gas and electricity.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Electricity generation comes from a range of technologies and operators.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] ElectraNet operates the high-voltage electricity transmission network.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] SA Power Networks distributes electricity to end users.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The largest electricity and gas retailing companies are also the largest generating companies.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The largest fossil fuel power stations are the Torrens Island Power Station gas-fired plant operated by AGL Energy and the Pelican Point Power Station operated by Engie.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has wind and solar power and connections to the national grid.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Gas is supplied from the Moomba Gas Processing Plant in the Cooper Basin via the Moomba Adelaide Pipeline System and the SEAGas pipeline from Victoria.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2011, South Australia generated 18% of its electricity from wind power, and had 51% of the installed capacity of wind generators in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Due to almost universal blackouts within the city during September 2016, the state worked with Tesla to produce the world's largest electricity battery at Hornsdale Power Reserve which has increased that state's electrical security to the extent in which large blackouts are no longer an event.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The provision of water services is by the government-owned SA Water.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's water is supplied from its seven reservoirs: Mount Bold, Happy Valley, Myponga, Millbrook, Hope Valley, Little Para and South Para.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The yield from these reservoir catchments can be as little as 10% of the city's requirements (90GL per annum) in drought years and about 60% in average years.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The remaining demand is met by the pumping of water from the River Murray.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] A sea-water desalination plant capable of supplying 100GL per annum was built during the 2001–2009 drought; however, it operated at about 8% of its capacity until 2019.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In December 2018, the State and Federal Governments agreed to fund a $2m study to determine how the plant could be used to reduce reliance on river water, in an effort to help save the Murray River basin and mouth (including the Coorong) from further ecological damage.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] AdelaideFree WiFi is a citywide free Wi-Fi network covering most of the inner city areas of Adelaide, primarily the Adelaide CBD and Northern Adelaide precincts.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It was officially launched at the Adelaide Central Markets on Tuesday 25 June 2014.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It was originally provided by Internode with infrastructure provided by outdoor Cisco WiFi N access points attached to the top of lighting poles, as well as inside cafes and businesses across the city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2023, a new agreement was reached between the City of Adelaide and TPG Telecom to replace the network infrastructure, improving network speed and coverage.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide, was a 10 sail composite (timber planking on a wrought-iron frame) clipper.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It was rescued from the mooring where it sank, as HMS Carrick, in Glasgow in 1991.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] In 2001 it was decided that the ship's name would be reverted to the City of Adelaide, formally renamed in 2013, and arrived in Port Adelaide on 3 February 2014.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] It was not until June 2024 that the ship was moved from the barge Bradley by Wallbridge Gilbert Aztec (WGA) to the current home on Dock 2, as the centerpiece of a planned village in Port Adelaide's inner harbour.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The ship is owned by the Clipper Ship City of Adelaide Ltd (CSCOAL).
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The STV One and All, a 42-metre two-masted square-rigged brigantine and the ketch *The Failie* are moored at McLaren Wharf.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide has been involved in the sister cities movement since 1972.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] As of 2023 it has long-term international partnership arrangements with five cities, known as sister cities, based on formal agreements between Adelaide and each city.
[src:hugh-possingham/adelaide-p02] This allows collaboration in the cultural, educational, business, and technical spheres.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Applied ecology is an integrated treatment of the ecological, social, and biotechnological aspects of natural resource conservation and management.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Applied ecology typically focuses on geomorphology, soils, and plant communities as the underpinnings for vegetation and wildlife (both game and non-game) management.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Applied ecology includes all disciplines that are related to human activities so that it does not only cover agriculture, forestry and fisheries but also global change.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] The first involves the outputs or those fields that address the use and management of the environment, particularly for its ecosystem services and exploitable resources.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] The second are the inputs or those that are concerned with the management strategies or human influences on the ecosystem or biodiversity.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] The discipline is often linked to ecological management on the grounds that the effective management of natural ecosystems depends on ecological knowledge.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] It often uses an ecological approach to solve problems of specific parts of the environment, which can involve the comparison of plausible options (e.g. best management options).
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] The role of applied science in agricultural production has been brought into greater focus as fluctuations in global food production feed through into prices and availability to consumers.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Applied ecologists often use one or more of the following approaches, namely, observation, experimentation, and modeling.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] For example, a wildlife preservation project could involve: observational studies of the wildlife ecology; experiments to understand causal relationships; and the application of modeling to determine the information beyond the scope of experimentation.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] The ecological approach used in applied ecology could include inputs from management strategies such as conservation biology, restoration ecology, global change, ecotoxicology, biomonitoring, biodiversity, environmental policies, and economics, among others.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Restoration ecology is a particularly prominent strategy in the discipline since it applies the principles of restoring and repairing damaged ecological systems to their original state.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Like those used in ecological theory, many areas of the discipline employ approaches that are based on simple statistical and analytic models (e.g. spatial models) as well as those with mathematical properties (e.g. matrix models).
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] There is also the digital computer simulation modeling, which is designed to solve statistical ecology problems and to achieve bioeconomic goals such as the forecasting and the evaluation of consequences for specific activities.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Applied ecology also requires human interest, particularly the exercise of judgments of relative values and goals.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] Applied ecology can be applied to the economic development process.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-ecology] The discipline, for example, can be integrated into the national economic planning to comprehensively address environmental concerns since these problems are intersectoral and interdisciplinary in nature.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] In the past, practical applications have motivated the development of mathematical theories, which then became the subject of study in pure mathematics where abstract concepts are studied for their own sake.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The activity of applied mathematics is thus intimately connected with research in pure mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Historically, applied mathematics consisted principally of applied analysis, most notably differential equations; approximation theory (broadly construed, to include representations, asymptotic methods, variational methods, and numerical analysis); and applied probability.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] These areas of mathematics related directly to the development of Newtonian physics, and in fact, the distinction between mathematicians and physicists was not sharply drawn before the mid-19th century.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Engineering and computer science departments have traditionally made use of applied mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Today, the term "applied mathematics" is used in a broader sense.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] It includes the classical areas noted above as well as other areas that have become increasingly important in applications.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Even fields such as number theory that are part of pure mathematics are now important in applications (such as cryptography), though they are not generally considered to be part of the field of applied mathematics *per se*.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] There is no consensus as to what the various branches of applied mathematics are.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Such categorizations are made difficult by the way mathematics and science change over time, and also by the way universities organize departments, courses, and degrees.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Many mathematicians distinguish between "applied mathematics", which is concerned with mathematical methods, and the "applications of mathematics" within science and engineering.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] A biologist using a population model and applying known mathematics would not be *doing* applied mathematics, but rather *using* it; however, mathematical biologists have posed problems that have stimulated the growth of pure mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Mathematicians such as Poincaré and Arnold deny the existence of "applied mathematics" and claim that there are only "applications of mathematics." Similarly, non-mathematicians blend applied mathematics and applications of mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The use and development of mathematics to solve industrial problems is also called "industrial mathematics".
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] These are often considered interdisciplinary.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Sometimes, the term **applicable mathematics** is used to distinguish between the traditional applied mathematics that developed alongside physics and the many areas of mathematics that are applicable to real-world problems today, although there is no consensus as to a precise definition.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Mathematicians often distinguish between "applied mathematics" on the one hand, and the "applications of mathematics" or "applicable mathematics" both within and outside of science and engineering, on the other.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Some mathematicians emphasize the term applicable mathematics to separate or delineate the traditional applied areas from new applications arising from fields that were previously seen as pure mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] For example, from this viewpoint, an ecologist or geographer using population models and applying known mathematics would not be doing applied, but rather applicable, mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Other authors prefer describing *applicable mathematics* as a union of "new" mathematical applications with the traditional fields of applied mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] With this outlook, the terms applied mathematics and applicable mathematics are thus interchangeable.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Historically, mathematics was most important in the natural sciences and engineering.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] However, since World War II, fields outside the physical sciences have spawned the creation of new areas of mathematics, such as game theory and social choice theory, which grew out of economic considerations.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Further, the utilization and development of mathematical methods expanded into other areas leading to the creation of new fields such as mathematical finance and data science.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Statistics is probably the most widespread mathematical science used in the social sciences.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Academic institutions are not consistent in the way they group and label courses, programs, and degrees in applied mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] At some schools, there is a single mathematics department, whereas others have separate departments for Applied Mathematics and (Pure) Mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] It is very common for Statistics departments to be separated at schools with graduate programs, but many undergraduate-only institutions include statistics under the mathematics department.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Many applied mathematics programs (as opposed to departments) consist primarily of cross-listed courses and jointly appointed faculty in departments representing applications.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Some Ph.D. programs in applied mathematics require little or no coursework outside mathematics, while others require substantial coursework in a specific area of application.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] In some respects this difference reflects the distinction between "application of mathematics" and "applied mathematics".
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Some universities in the U.K. host departments of *Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics*, but it is now much less common to have separate departments of pure and applied mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] A notable exception to this is the Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics at the University of Cambridge, housing the Lucasian Professor of Mathematics whose past holders include Isaac Newton, Charles Babbage, James Lighthill, Paul Dirac, and Stephen Hawking.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Schools with separate applied mathematics departments range from Brown University, which has a large Division of Applied Mathematics that offers degrees through the doctorate, to Santa Clara University, which offers only the M.S. in applied mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Research universities dividing their mathematics department into pure and applied sections include MIT.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Students in this program also learn another skill (computer science, engineering, physics, pure math, etc.) to supplement their applied math skills.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Mathematics is used in all branches of engineering and has subsequently developed as distinct specialties within the engineering profession.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] For example, continuum mechanics is foundational to civil, Mechanical engineering and aerospace engineering, with courses in solid mechanics and fluid mechanics being important components of the engineering curriculum.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Continuum mechanics is also an important branch of mathematics in its own right.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] It has served as the inspiration for a vast range of difficult research questions for mathematicians involved in the analysis of partial differential equations, differential geometry and the calculus of variations.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Perhaps the most well-known mathematical problem posed by a continuum mechanical system is the question of Navier-Stokes existence and smoothness.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Prominent career mathematicians rather than engineers who have contributed to the mathematics of continuum mechanics are Clifford Truesdell, Walter Noll, Andrey Kolmogorov and George Batchelor.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] An essential discipline for many fields in engineering is that of control engineering.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The associated mathematical theory of this specialism is control theory, a branch of applied mathematics that builds off the mathematics of dynamical systems.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Control theory has played a significant enabling role in modern technology, serving a foundational role in electrical, mechanical and aerospace engineering.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Like continuum mechanics, control theory has also become a field of mathematical research in its own right, with mathematicians such as Aleksandr Lyapunov, Norbert Wiener, Lev Pontryagin and Fields Medal recipient Pierre-Louis Lions contributing to its foundations.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Scientific computing includes applied mathematics (especially numerical analysis), computing science (especially high-performance computing), and mathematical modelling in a scientific discipline.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Computer science relies on logic, algebra, discrete mathematics such as graph theory, and combinatorics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Operations research and management science are often taught in faculties of engineering, business, and public policy.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Applied mathematics has substantial overlap with the discipline of statistics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Statistical theorists study and improve statistical procedures with mathematics, and statistical research often raises mathematical questions.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Statistical theory relies on probability and decision theory, and makes extensive use of scientific computing, analysis, and optimization; for the design of experiments, statisticians use algebra and combinatorial design.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Applied mathematicians and statisticians often work in a department of mathematical sciences (particularly at colleges and small universities).
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Actuarial science applies probability, statistics, and economic theory to assess risk in insurance, finance and other industries and professions.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Mathematical economics is the application of mathematical methods to represent theories and analyze problems in economics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The applied methods usually refer to nontrivial mathematical techniques or approaches.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Mathematical economics is based on statistics, probability, mathematical programming (as well as other computational methods), operations research, game theory, and some methods from mathematical analysis.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] In this regard, it resembles (but is distinct from) financial mathematics, another part of applied mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] with MSC2010 classifications for 'Game theory' at codes 91Axx Archived 2015-04-02 at the Wayback Machine and for 'Mathematical economics' at codes 91Bxx Archived 2015-04-02 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The line between applied mathematics and specific areas of application is often blurred.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] Many universities teach mathematical and statistical courses outside the respective departments, in departments and areas including business, engineering, physics, chemistry, psychology, biology, computer science, scientific computation, information theory, and mathematical physics.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics is an international applied mathematics organization.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] As of 2024, the society has 14,000 individual members.
[src:hugh-possingham/applied-mathematics] The American Mathematics Society has its Applied Mathematics Group.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The website has come under scrutiny from many governments starting in the late 2010s, including bans in China and Russia and in 2025 U.S.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed a domain registrar to identify the owner of archive.today's domain name.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] archive.today was founded in 2012 as a web archive.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] It allegedly registered its trademark in the Czech Republic in 2013.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The site originally branded itself as archive.today, but changed the primary mirror to archive.is in May 2015.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] It began to deprecate the archive.is domain in favor of other mirrors in January 2019.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] According to the archive.today blog, the website had saved about 500 million pages by 2021, 700 terabytes in total size.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In July 2013, archive.today began supporting the API of the Memento Project at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Due to budget constraints at LANL, the Memento Project was disestablished in September 2025.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Archive.today was one of the last major active users of the Memento protocol following the project's downsizing.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The closure of the Memento infrastructure at LANL in September 2025 came amid a broader period of increased scrutiny for the service.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Individual profile pages on 200.zona.media link to snapshots of social media posts by relatives, obituaries in local media, and other open-source evidence used to verify each death.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In early 2023, a team of researchers at the University of Amsterdam identified archive.today as the most-used open-access archiving service among fact-checking organisations, based on the European Digital Media Observatory's dataset on the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] On 5 August 2023, Jani Patokallio published on his blog *Gyrovague* an investigation regarding archive.today's funding sources and the founder's identity.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] On 30 October 2025, the US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed archive.today's domain registrar, Tucows.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The subpoena stated its purpose was to identify the owner(s) of the archive.today domain name, and that it was part of a criminal investigation conducted by the FBI, the nature of which was not disclosed.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] News coverage of the subpoena mentioned Patokallio's report, where Patokallio has said there were "several indications" the founder was based in Russia.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In November 2025, the DNS provider AdGuard DNS reported that a French organization *Web Abuse Association Defense* (WAAD) had pressured it to block archive.today and its mirror domains.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] WAAD alleged that archive.today had refused to remove child sexual abuse material since 2023.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] When AdGuard contacted archive.today, the archive removed the material, stating that it had never received prior complaints about those URLs.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] AdGuard found WAAD suspicious as a recently registered association with minimal public presence, noting evidence of possible impersonation of a real French lawyer in similar WAAD complaints sent to other companies.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] AdGuard announced it would file a criminal complaint with French police.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] On 14 January 2026, it emerged that archive.today had silently modified its CAPTCHA page to send repeated requests to *Gyrovague*, thereby causing visitors to unwittingly contribute to a DDOS attack against the blog.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The archive.today blog simultaneously posted several public criticisms of Patokallio.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Emails released by Patokallio show archive.today requesting the temporary removal of his report and later threatening him with AI pornography.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The community's decision was made despite concerns over maintaining content verifiability—partly undermined by the discovery of the alterations— while removing and replacing the second-largest archiving service used across the Wikimedia Foundation's projects.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The Wikimedia Foundation had stated its readiness to take action regardless of the community verdict.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Patokallio expressed his satisfaction with the outcome.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] This was not the first time Wikipedia had restricted links to archive.today.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In 2013, the community blacklisted archive.is, citing concerns about botnets, linkspamming, and the opaque manner in which the site was operated.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The decision was overturned in 2016 following a new request for comment, and archive.today was removed from the spam blacklist.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] At the time of the 2026 ban, the site was the second-largest archiving service used across all Wikimedia Foundation projects, with over 695,000 links spread across approximately 400,000 pages.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] archive.today can capture individual pages in response to explicit user requests.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Since its beginning, it has supported crawling pages with URLs containing the now-deprecated hash-bang fragment (#!).
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The website records only text and images, excluding XML, RTF, spreadsheet (xls or ods) and other non-static content.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] However, videos for certain sites, like Twitter, are saved.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] It keeps track of the history of snapshots saved, requesting confirmation before adding a new snapshot of an already saved page.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Once a web page is archived, it cannot be deleted directly by any Internet user.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Pages are captured at a browser width of 1,024 pixels.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] CSS is converted to inline CSS, removing responsive web design and selectors such as `:hover` and `:active`.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Content generated using JavaScript during the crawling process appears in a frozen state.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] HTML class names are preserved inside the `old-class` attribute.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] When text is selected, a JavaScript applet generates a URL fragment seen in the browser's address bar that automatically highlights that portion of the text when visited again.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Web pages can be duplicated from archive.today to web.archive.org as second-level backup, but archive.today does not save its snapshots in WARC format.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The reverse—from web.archive.org to archive.today—is also possible, but the copy usually takes more time than a direct capture.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] While saving a page, a list of URLs for individual page elements and their content sizes, HTTP statuses and MIME types is shown.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] This list can only be viewed during the crawling process.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Removing advertisements, popups or expanding links from archived pages is possible by asking the owner to do it on his blog.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] According to the site's FAQ, archive.today's storage layer runs on Apache Hadoop and Apache Accumulo, with all data stored on the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Textual content is replicated three times across servers in two data centers, both located in Europe, with at least one hosted by the French provider OVH; images are replicated twice.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The site does not store snapshots in WARC format.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The scraping component has used a modified version of the Chromium browser since November 2019, replacing the previous PhantomJS-based engine.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The research toolbar enables advanced keywords operators, using `*` as the wildcard character.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Paired quotation marks address the search to an exact sequence of keywords present in the title or in the body of the webpage, whereas the *insite* operator restricts it to a specific Internet domain.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] While saving a dynamic list, archive.today search box shows only a result that links the previous and the following section of the list (e.g.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The other web pages saved are filtered, and sometimes may be found by one of their occurrences.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The search feature is backed by Google CustomSearch.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] If it delivers no results, archive.today attempts to utilize Yandex Search.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] archive.today is frequently used to bypass paywalls on news websites, similarly to the defunct service 12ft.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The practice of sharing archive.today links to circumvent paywalls has sparked legal and ethical debate in Europe.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In the Netherlands, journalist Peter Aanzee publicly challenged a physician who shared an archive.ph link to one of his paywalled articles in *De Volkskrant*, arguing that distributing archived copies constituted copyright infringement.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Commentators have contrasted archive.today with the Internet Archive's Wayback Machine.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The same paywalled *Volkskrant* article shared via archive.ph was also found archived in the Wayback Machine, demonstrating that both services can be used to circumvent paywalls.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Like the Wayback Machine, archive.today does not advertise paywall circumvention among its stated features; the ability to bypass paywalls is a byproduct of its core function of archiving web pages as they appear to visitors.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] A 2025 investigation by journalist Henk van Ess found that AI chatbots—including ChatGPT, Perplexity AI, Grok, and Claude—exploit web archives to bypass paywalls during live web searches.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In one documented case, ChatGPT retrieved a full article from *The Economist* via archive.today and then generated a five-point economic analysis in the publication's characteristic style and terminology.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Van Ess identified six distinct methods of paywall circumvention by AI systems, of which "archive exploitation"—finding archived copies on services such as archive.today and the Internet Archive—was the most direct.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Unlike documented concerns about AI training unpaywalled content, this behaviour involves real-time retrieval through archived copies during individual queries, effectively extending paywall circumvention beyond human users to automated agents.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The researchers documented that archive.is URLs were extensively shared on "fringe" communities such as 4chan's /pol/ board and the Reddit subreddit r/The_Donald, both to preserve potentially contentious content and to deny ad revenue to news outlets perceived as ideologically opposed.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Moderation bots on r/The_Donald automatically blocked direct links to certain news sites—for example, 46% of links to the *New York Daily News* were censored—and prompted users to post archive.is URLs instead.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] The authors estimated that *The Washington Post* lost approximately US$70,000 per year in ad revenue due to the practice of sharing archived copies rather than direct links on Reddit alone.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] On Reddit, bots were responsible for posting 44% of archive.is links and 85% of Wayback Machine links across the studied subreddits, driven by moderators aiming to mitigate link rot.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] A 2023 study by researchers at the University of Amsterdam, as part of the vera.ai project, examined 1,991 fact-checking articles from the European Digital Media Observatory's "War in Ukraine" dataset.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Of 41,758 extracted links, 6,002 were archived pages. archive.today was the most-used link archiving service, at 44.1%, ahead of the Internet Archive/Wayback Machine (29.2%) and Perma.cc (26.6%).
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Fact-checkers primarily used these services to preserve ephemeral and platform-restricted content, such as Facebook posts that are difficult to capture due to anti-bot measures.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In March 2019, the site was blocked for six months by several internet providers in Australia and New Zealand in the aftermath of the Christchurch mosque shootings in an attempt to limit distribution of the footage of the attack.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] According to GreatFire.org, archive.today has been blocked in mainland China since March 2016, archive.li since September 2017, archive.fo since July 2018, as well as archive.ph since December 2019.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] On 21 July 2015, the archive.today blocked access to the service from all Finnish IP addresses, stating on Twitter that they did this in order to avoid escalating a dispute they allegedly had with the Finnish government.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] Since the conflict with the Finnish blogger in early 2026, the website displays an unpassable captcha to visitors from Finland.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] In 2016, the Russian communications agency Roskomnadzor began blocking access to archive.is from Russia.
[src:hugh-possingham/archive-today] On 23 March 2026, archive.today and several mirror domains were blocked by Russian authorities.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:hugh-possingham/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The **Australian Academy of Science** is a scientific academy.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] It was founded in 1954 by a group of distinguished Australians, including Australian Fellows of the Royal Society of London, after its forerunner, the **Australian National Research Council** had been dissolved.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Academy Secretariat is in Canberra, at the Shine Dome.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] On 21 August 1919 the Australasian Research Council, based in Sydney, was established to represent Australia on the International Research Council.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The council was formalised by the Australasian Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS) and renamed the Australian National Research Council (ANRC) in July 1921.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The new academy was established in 1954, and, after it had assumed most of functions of the ANRC, the ANRC was dissolved in 1955, the final meeting taking place in Canberra on 16 August 1955.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The academy was founded by a group of Australians, among them Australian Fellows of the Royal Society in London.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The first president was Sir Mark Oliphant.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Australian Academy of Science is modelled after the Royal Society, and operates under a Royal charter; as such, it is an independent body, but it has government endorsement.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The objectives of the academy are to promote science and science education through a wide range of activities; officially "promoting, declaring and disseminating scientific knowledge".
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The academy also runs the 22 National Committees for Science, which provide a forum to discuss issues relevant to all the scientific disciplines in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Australian Academy of Science has been producing educational resources since 1967.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Its first published resource was *Biological* *Science: the Web of Life,* authored by David Morgan.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Academy supports the development of evidence-based education programs in science and mathematics.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] As of 2025, the Academy delivers three programs: Primary Connections for primary school science education, Science Connections for secondary school science education, and a combined mathematics program called reSolve.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] In 2003, the Australian Academy of Science began research on how to best support teachers of science and mathematics subjects through pedagogical-based resources rather than content-based resources.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] By 2005, the Australian Government announced they would support the program Primary Connections through the Department of Education, Science and Training (DEST) under the Australian Government Quality Teacher Programme in establishing eight curriculum units, developed and trialed in 2005.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Australian Government wanted to use the program to "improve learning outcomes in science and literacy through a sophisticated professional learning program supported with rich curriculum resources that will improve teachers' knowledge of science and science teaching".
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] 106 trial teachers participated in 56 trial schools across Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] At this time, Primary Connections used hard-copy and digital materials constructed for teachers to adapt to primary school classrooms based closely on the 5Es model of learning which had served as the foremost pedagogical structure for teaching in science education.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Primary Connections has been reported to have a 'positive impact on schools, teachers, and students'.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Currently, the Academy's education programs are funded by the Department of Education to improve teacher confidence and capability in teaching mathematics and science.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Since 2020, Primary Connections has had an increasing focus on interactivity for students, piloting online professional learning, and research and review of the development of STEM teacher resources.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] As part of a review of teacher needs, Primary Connections ended the sale of hard-copy resources at the end of 2020.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] In addition, the Primary Connections and its sister program Science Connections (launched in 2025) are constructed around a new learning structure: the Launch, Inquire, Act (LIA) Framework.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The LIA Framework was designed to address a stated need from surveyed teachers for an online resource that allows teachers to readily select, adapt and build their own program of work within the framework of Australia's science curriculum.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The LIA Framework begins with the "Launch" phase, which was designed to engage students and provide both motivation and context for their learning.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Launch phase encourages students to begin scientific inquiry on a topic through common experiences that connect with their lives (for example, by having students walk into a darkened classroom with all electricity turned off to demonstrate the importance of electricity).
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] This allows all students to develop a common language and provides equity in learning.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Next is the "Inquire" phase, which consists of cycles of inquiry, promoting deepening understanding.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Students improve their knowledge of a topic via questioning, investigations, and contextual integration (for example, how a torch can be made with a battery, wires, and a bulb: experimenting with different forms of circuits).
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The last phase, "Act", aims to empower students to act on their newly acquired knowledge and skills.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] It encourages students to have agency by designing new ways to interact with the world via science (for example, using their circuitry experiments to design an electrical product to support people in a blackout).
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Shine Dome (previously known as Becker House) is a well-known Canberra landmark, notable for its unusual structure, and colloquially referred to as "The Martian Embassy", an allusion to its shape and the fact that as the capital of Australia, Canberra is the home of foreign embassies.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] It was designed by architect Sir Roy Grounds, of Grounds, Romberg and Boyd.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] When completed in 1959 its 45.75-metre-diameter dome was the largest in Australia.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] On 1 December 1956, the academy's building design committee met in Adelaide to look over plans submitted by six architects.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The plan accepted involved a 710-tonne reinforced concrete dome, which had to be supported by 16 thin supports.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The concrete is approximately 60 cm thick at the base supports, and 10 cm at the top.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The dome supports itself, with no internal wall holding it up.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The foundation stone, laid on 2 May 1958 by Prime Minister of Australia, Robert Menzies, was originally part of the pier of the Great Melbourne Telescope constructed in 1869 under the supervision of the Royal Society and transferred to Mount Stromlo Observatory in the 1940s.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The building was named Becker House, for benefactor and Fellow of the Academy Sir Jack Ellerton Becker, in 1962.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] In 2000, it was renamed in honour of Fellow John Shine, who donated one million dollars to renovate the dome.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] In 2016, the dome appeared in the television documentary series about Australian modernist architecture *Streets of Your Town* presented by Tim Ross.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] On 20 January 2020 the Dome was seriously damaged by a hailstorm with smashed skylights and denting of the copper roof surface.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The Fellowship of the Australian Academy of Science is made up of around 500 leading Australian scientists.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Scientists judged by their peers to have made an exceptional contribution to knowledge in their field may be elected to Fellowship of the academy.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Twenty new Fellows may be elected every year.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] No more than two Fellows may be elected every three years on the basis of distinguished contributions to science by means other than personal research.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] A small number of distinguished foreign scientists with substantial connections to Australian science are elected as Corresponding Members.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] Fellows are denoted by the letters **FAA** (Fellow of the Australian Academy of Science) after their name.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] There are three other learned Academies in Australia, those of Humanities (Australian Academy of the Humanities), Social Science (Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia) and Technological Sciences and Engineering (Australian Academy of Technological Sciences and Engineering).
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-academy-of-science] The four Academies cooperate through the Australian Council of Learned Academies, formed in 2010.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] The **Australian Laureate Fellowship** is an Australian professorial research fellowship awarded by the Australian Research Council.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] Fellows are chosen each year for five-year awards.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] In 2023 8 industry-focused Laureate Fellowships were awarded for the first time.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] In 2010, the Australian Research Council created the Kathleen Fitzpatrick and Georgina Sweet Australian Laureate Fellowships.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] The Kathleen Fitzpatrick fellowship is named for Kathleen Fitzpatrick and honours a woman candidate in a humanities field.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] The Georgina Sweet fellowship is named for Georgina Sweet and honours a woman in a science or technology discipline.
[src:hugh-possingham/australian-laureate-fellowship] In addition to the funding from the standard Australian laureate fellowship, both of these named fellowships include an additional $20,000 per year to promote women in research.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Possingham received his bachelor's degree with Honours in 1984, from the department of Applied Mathematics at the University of Adelaide.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He completed his D.Phil. at Oxford University under Michael Bulmer in 1987, on a Rhodes Scholarship.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] His thesis focused on optimal foraging theory.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Possingham's first postdoctoral position was with Joan Roughgarden at Stanford University, working on the recruitment dynamics of intertidal communities.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He then returned to Australia on a QEII Fellowship at the Australian National University, and undertook research on applications of population viability analysis to conservation biology.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He moved to the University of Adelaide, first as a lecturer, then in 1995 as a professor.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] In 2000 Possingham moved to a chair in the departments of Mathematics and Biological Sciences at the University of Queensland in Brisbane, where he was an ARC Professorial, Federation, and Laureate Fellow.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He was Director of the Australian Research Council Centre of Excellence for Environmental Decisions, and the Australian government's Threatened Species Recovery Hub.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] In 2016 he joined The Nature Conservancy as its Chief Scientist.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] During his academic career, Possingham has published over 650 peer-reviewed papers, and supervised 135 doctoral and postdoctoral researchers.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He co-developed the Marxan software for systematic conservation planning, which is considered "the most significant contribution to conservation biology to emerge from Australia's research community".
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] It has been used to plan terrestrial and marine protected area networks for 5% of the Earth's surface, including Australia's Great Barrier Reef.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Possingham was the Queensland Chief Scientist from 2020 to 2022, where he provided high-level strategic science, research and innovation advice to the Queensland Government and acted as an ambassador for science in Queensland.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Possingham is a member of the Wentworth Group of Concerned Scientists, chaired the Australian Government's committees on Biodiversity Hotspots, and on Biological Diversity, the Queensland Government's Smart State Council, and the Wilderness Society's Wild Country Science Council.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Possingham co-authored "The Brigalow Declaration" with Dr Barry Traill, used by Queensland Premier Beattie to support an end to land-clearing in Queensland.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Land clearance in Queensland was removing 500,000 hectares of native vegetation each year, and was responsible for 10% of Australia's greenhouse gas emissions; its cessation enabled Australia to meet its Kyoto Protocol target.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] In 2009 he proposed devoting a proportionate fraction of gambling revenues to saving an endangered species, to be selected by a random drawing shown on television before the Melbourne Cup.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] From 2016 to 2020, Possingham was the Chief Scientist of The Nature Conservancy, a global conservation organisation with 400 scientists and 4000 staff, that has protected more than 40 million hectares of land and thousands of kilometres of rivers worldwide.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] Possingham won the Australian Mathematical Society Medal, the inaugural Fenner Medal for plant and animal biology from the Australian Academy of Science, and the 1999 and 2009 Eureka Prizes for Environmental Research.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] In 2016 he was awarded the Mahathir Science Award for Tropical Natural Resources, alongside Kerrie Wilson and Eric Meijard.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He was elected to the Australian Academy of Science in 2005.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] In 2013, Possigham was the first Australian to be elected a fellow of the Ecological Society of America, and in 2016 he was elected a foreign associate of the USA National Academy of Sciences.
[src:hugh-possingham/hugh-possingham] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in 2025.
